Preamble

CERN has developed this licence to promote collaboration among hardware designers
and to provide a legal framework that supports the free use, study, modification,
and sharing of hardware designs and documentation.

The CERN-OHL-S is a strongly reciprocal licence that ensures that any distributed
modifications or derivatives of this design must remain open under the same terms.

1. Definitions

'Licence' means this CERN Open Hardware Licence Version 2 - Strongly Reciprocal.

'Documentation' means schematic diagrams, HDL code (such as Verilog, VHDL, SystemVerilog),
PCB layouts, mechanical drawings, simulations, and any other information that
describes the hardware design.

'Product' means any device or physical object manufactured based on the Documentation.

'Licensee' means any person or legal entity exercising rights under this Licence.

2. Grant of Licence

CERN grants you a worldwide, royalty-free, non-exclusive licence to use, copy,
study, modify, and distribute the Documentation, and to manufacture or distribute
Products based on it, under the conditions described in this Licence.

3. Conditions

a. Any distribution of modified Documentation or Products must:
   - Be released under this same licence (CERN-OHL-S-2.0),
   - Clearly indicate the changes made,
   - Attribute credit to the original author(s).

b. You may not impose any additional restrictions beyond those in this Licence.

c. You must keep all copyright, licence and attribution notices intact.

4. Warranty and Liability

The Documentation and any Products are provided "as is", without warranty of any kind,
express or implied, including but not limited to warranties of merchantability,
fitness for a particular purpose, or non-infringement.

In no event shall the Licensor be liable for any claim, damages or other liability,
whether in an action of contract, tort or otherwise, arising from or in connection
with the Documentation or the use thereof.

5. Termination

If you breach the terms of this Licence, your rights under it will terminate automatically.
You may reinstate your rights by remedying the violation within 30 days of becoming
aware of it.

6. Versioning

CERN may publish revised versions of the CERN Open Hardware Licence. You may choose
to continue using this version or adopt a later one.

7. Notices

